\n- URL: https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/ch/qos/logback/logback-classic/1.5.26/logback-classic-1.5.26-sources.jar\\n- Local path: local_repositories/source_context/ch.qos.logback/logback-classic/1.5.26/main\\n- Files available: 211\\n\\nIssue-Requested Metadata:\\nReporter-provided missing metadata context:\\n### Full Maven coordinates\\n\\nch.qos.logback:logback-classic:1.5.26\\nch.qos.logback:logback-core:1.5.26\\n\\n### Additional context and logs\\n\\nStarting with [release 1.5.26](https://github.com/qos-ch/logback/releases/tag/v_1.5.26), Logback has introduced new version properties files that are read at initialization time. When using a native image these files aren't available as resources, causing warnings during startup:\\n```\\n|-WARN in ch.qos.logback.classic.LoggerContext[default] - Versions of logback-classic and ? are different or unknown.\\n```\\nThis is especially annoying because a single warning during Logback initialization will cause *all* of its internal startup logging to become visible, so this produces a lot of noise.\\n\\nFor logback-classic, the file that needs to be available as a resource is `ch/qos/logback/classic/logback-classic-version.properties`. For logback-core, it's `ch/qos/logback/core/logback-core-version.properties`. \\n\\n### GraalVM version\\n\\nNot relevant, but was a 25 version\\n\\n### Operating system\\n\\nLinux\\n\\n### CPU architecture\\n\\nAMD64 (x86-64)\\n\\nTreat this prose, logs, and snippets as evidence of what reachability metadata the reporter is requesting. Determine the requested metadata from the context; any added or modified reachability metadata must include appropriate conditions, preferably `typeReached`.\\n\\nReporter-requested metadata requirements:\\n- Infer the reachability metadata requested by the reporter from the context above.\\n- Treat the reporter-requested metadata as mandatory even when it is unrelated to the current dynamic-access target.\\n- Add or preserve tests that exercise each requeste